**Project Information**

This project was completed for COMP 5710/6710 as part of a semester-long exploration into professional software quality assurance practices. Our team, ICONIC4, consisted of three members: Andrea McCarroll, Amy Prieto, Grayson Ryoo and Matthew Glass. The project required integrating fuzz testing, forensic logging, and continuous integration (CI) into the existing MLForensics Python project. The team’s goal was to introduce reliability, diagnostics, and automated testing into a project that originally lacked these capabilities.

**Objective**

The primary objective of this project was to apply SQA techniques learned in class into a real Python codebase. The goal was not just to generate artifacts but to practice integrating fuzzing, logging, error analysis, and CI in a meaningful way. The MLForensics project was intentionally imperfect so that our SQA tools, fuzzer, forensic logger, and CI pipeline, could uncover faults and point toward more robust software engineering practices. By the end of the project, the software would be significantly more testable, observable, and stable.

**Repository Setup**

The MLForensics project was unzipped and uploaded to GitHub as a new public repository named ICONIC4-FALL2025-SQA, following the assignment specifications. The repository is available at:

https://github.com/bam130/ICONIC4-FALL2025-SQA/tree/main

Once uploaded, a README.md file was added containing team information, instructions, and descriptions of the integrated SQA components. The repository structure was reorganized slightly to make room for the new files:

- fuzz.py – the fuzz tester  
- forensics\_logger.py – centralized logging  
- .github/workflows/sqa-ci.yml – CI automation  
- logs/forensics.log – runtime forensic output  
- fuzz-results.log and fuzz-summary.json – fuzzer output  
- SQA-REPO.md – this report

**Software Quality Assurance Activities**  
Fuzz Testing

Fuzz testing was implemented using a custom-developed script, fuzz.py, which is included in the root of the repository. The fuzzer was specifically crafted to interact with five MLForensics functions:

- parse\_python\_file()  
- LintEngine.run()  
- compute\_token\_frequency()  
- Report.generate()  
- mine\_git\_repo()

These target functions come from different areas of the MLForensics codebase—parsing, linting, frequency computation, report generation, and git repository mining—so they gave the fuzzer wide behavioral coverage.

The fuzzer uses randomized file paths, random Python-like code, temporary files, random strings, and random statistics objects to stress-test these functions. The script attempts imports using a robust fallback mechanism:

- def try\_import(module\_name, attr):  ...

This is necessary because the MLForensics modules have inconsistent naming patterns. The fuzzer automatically logs each failure to fuzz-results.log in JSON format, along with a summary file (fuzz-summary.json) that CI can use to determine pass/fail status.

The fuzzer also exits with status 1 if any failure occurs:

if FAILURES:  
    sys.exit(1)

This guarantees that GitHub Actions treats unexpected errors as build failures.

Forensics Logging Integration

To improve traceability and debugging, a dedicated logging module named forensics\_logger.py was written and integrated into five MLForensics functions. The logger records detailed runtime information including timestamps, filenames, line numbers, log levels, and messages.

The code uses a rotating file handler:

handler \= RotatingFileHandler("logs/forensics.log", maxBytes=500000, backupCount=3)

This prevents CI environments from being overwhelmed by large logs.Whenever one of the target functions is executed, the associated forensic logger records:

- Entry into the function  
- Input parameters  
- Key internal decisions  
- Exceptions with full tracebacks

This dramatically improves the inspectability of MLForensics. During fuzzing, the forensic logging proved essential for diagnosing the root causes of failures, especially when the fuzzer provided malformed input.

 Continuous Integration (GitHub Actions)

To automate testing, a CI workflow file named sqa-ci.yml was added in the .github/workflows directory. The workflow automatically:

- Checks out the repository  
- Sets up Python  
- Installs dependencies  
- Runs the fuzzer (python [fuzz.py](http://fuzz.py))  
- Uploads fuzz-results.log and fuzz-summary.json as artifacts  
- Fails the build if the fuzzer detects crashes

The CI integration means any commit that reintroduces a bug caught by the fuzzer will automatically fail. This provides stability and makes the repository safer for future development.

**Results and Observations**

The integration of fuzz testing, forensic logging, and CI significantly increased the robustness and maintainability of MLForensics. The fuzzer revealed multiple unhandled exceptions in the parser, frequency calculator, report generator, and git-mining functions—some of which would never be encountered through normal usage. The forensic logs allowed us to reconstruct exactly how inputs triggered failures. The CI workflow automated the process, ensuring that no commit could silently introduce new bugs.

Overall, the project provided a realistic demonstration of how professional software teams combine automated testing, structured logging, and CI pipelines to maintain high-quality codebases.

   
**Lessons Learned**

This project reinforced the importance of integrating multiple SQA practices rather than relying on a single method. Fuzz testing alone found bugs, but the forensic logging made these bugs understandable, and CI ensured they would not be reintroduced in future work. We learned that handling unexpected input is crucial for any real-world software tool. Additionally, we gained experience managing randomness, debugging nondeterministic crashes, and interpreting structured logs. This project provided practical insight into improving software resilience and developer workflow using industry-standard tools.

**Future Improvements**

Although the project successfully introduced SQA tools, several improvements could be made. Adding unit tests (e.g., via pytest) alongside fuzzing would help define expected behavior more clearly. Expanding the fuzzer to include grammar-based or mutation-based fuzzing would reveal deeper edge cases. More extensive type-checking or input-validation within MLForensics could prevent many crashes found during this project. Future CI workflows could integrate coverage reports or style/lint checks to further increase reliability.
